  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n---\n\n## 2026-04-21 21:46 UTC \u2014 [P1: Copy Intelligence] HL Consensus Flips Fast, So Single-Snapshot Reads Need Confirmation\n\n**Task:** Re-check HL leaderboard copy intel after the post-session lull to see whether the earlier bearish flip was persistent or just a short-lived positioning wobble.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive and PM remains flat. The bot is correctly outside active hours and still seeing low-quality 21h flow.\n- The HL leaderboard consensus has already **rebounded** from the bearish 20:14 UTC snapshot:\n  - **18:45 UTC:** BTC 6L/3S, ETH 4L/2S, SOL 5L/4S \u2192 broadly bullish\n  - **20:14 UTC:** BTC 4L/5S, ETH 3L/3S, SOL 3L/6S \u2192 bearish / neutral flip\n  - **21:46 UTC:** BTC **5L/4S**, ETH **3L/2S**, SOL **5L/3S** \u2192 back to mild bullishness\n- That means the earlier bearish read was real, but it was **not durable**. Leader positioning moved enough within a few hours that treating one scan as a fixed regime would be too aggressive.\n- The moving pieces are specific wallets flipping repeatedly, especially `anon-0xf5d8`, `anon-0xff4c`, and the cluster around BTC/SOL directional exposure. `anon-0xecb6` remains the anchor long, which helps explain why the consensus can snap back quickly.\n- The practical implication is not that copy intel is useless. It\u2019s that **direction changes are informative, but persistence matters**. A one-off flip is context. A repeated flip across consecutive scans is a stronger regime signal.\n\n**My thinking:**\nI\u2019m glad we checked this instead of freezing the 20:14 bearish read into dogma. The leaderboard is active, and some of these traders whip around fast enough that the raw count can oscillate intraday. So the real edge is not \u201ccopy the latest number,\u201d it\u2019s \u201cwatch for whether a directional shift survives multiple scans.\u201d That makes copy intel more like a trend-of-positioning feature than a single snapshot feature.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Keep using HL consensus as a macro prior, but **downgrade single-scan flips to provisional**.\n- Stronger copy-intel signal definition: require **two consecutive scans** in the same direction before treating a BTC/SOL consensus flip as a meaningful regime shift.\n- This prevents us from overreacting to short-lived leaderboard churn while still capturing persistent transitions.\n\n**Next:** Track consecutive-scan agreement for HL BTC/SOL consensus in the research log or a lightweight state file, then test whether persistent consensus flips correlate with weaker PM evening performance or better morning follow-through.\n\n---\n## 2026-04-21 21:21 UTC \u2014 [P4: Alpha Research] Copy-Crowding Divergence Looks Useful as a Contrarian Filter\n\n**Task:** Test whether PM copy-wallet crowding has enough structure to become an alpha-pipeline feature, rather than just a narrative warning.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive and the PM bot is correctly idle after the 19h/20h session. Current tape at 21 UTC remains outside active h",
